# Technical Architecture – Cab Booking System

## Technology Stack
- Frontend: React.js
- Backend: Node.js
- Framework: Express.js
- Database: MongoDB
- ODM: Mongoose
- Version Control: Git & GitHub

## Architecture Layers

### 1. Client Layer (React.js)
The client layer is the frontend of the application where users interact with the system.

Features:
- Cab Selection
- Booking Form
- Ride Tracking
- Login / Signup

### 2. API Layer (Express.js)
The API layer acts as a bridge between the frontend and backend.

REST APIs:
- POST /api/rides/book – Book a ride
- GET /api/users/:id – Get user details
- PUT /api/rides/:id – Update ride status
- DELETE /api/rides/:id – Cancel a ride

### 3. Service Layer
The service layer contains the business logic.

Responsibilities:
- Fare calculation
- Ride matching
- Ride tracking
- Ride status management

### 4. Data Access Layer (Mongoose)
The data access layer communicates with MongoDB.

Responsibilities:
- Create, Read, Update and Delete (CRUD) operations
- Define database schemas and models
- Connect the application to MongoDB

## Database Collections
- Users
- Drivers
- Rides
- Transactions

## Data Flow

1. User logs in.
2. User selects pickup and destination.
3. Booking request is sent to the Express API.
4. Service layer calculates the fare and assigns a driver.
5. Ride information is stored in MongoDB.
6. Driver and user receive real-time ride updates.

## Conclusion

The Cab Booking application follows the MERN stack architecture with separate frontend, backend, service, and database layers. This architecture makes the application scalable, maintainable, and easy to develop.
